04777nam a22006015i 9780822390589DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20082008ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223905897 a10.1515/97808223905892doi  a(DE-B1597)554461  a(OCoLC)1055301896  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aKK4450b.S3613 2008 7aLAW0180002bisacsh1 aSchmitt, Carl, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConstitutional Theory /cCarl Schmitt. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (488 p.) :b2 tables, 5 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection : 3300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tTranslator’s Preface -- tAn Introduction to Carl Schmitt’s Constitutional Theory: Issues and Context -- tConstitutional Theory -- tSchmitt’s Preface -- tPart I. Concept of the Constitution -- tPart II. The Rechtsstaat Component of the Modern Constitution -- tPart III. The Political Component of the Modern Constitution -- tPart IV. Constitutional Theory of the Federation -- tAppendix: The Weimar Constitution -- tNotes -- tBiographical Notes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCarl Schmitt’s magnum opus, Constitutional Theory, was originally published in 1928 and has been in print in German ever since. This volume makes Schmitt’s masterpiece of comparative constitutionalism available to English-language readers for the first time. Schmitt is considered by many to be one of the most original—and, because of his collaboration with the Nazi party, controversial—political thinkers of the twentieth century. In Constitutional Theory, Schmitt provides a highly distinctive and provocative interpretation of the Weimar Constitution. At the center of this interpretation lies his famous argument that the legitimacy of a constitution depends on a sovereign decision of the people. In addition to being subject to long-standing debate among legal and political theorists in Western Europe and the United States, this theory of constitution-making as decision has profoundly influenced constitutional theorists and designers in Asia, Latin America, and Eastern Europe.Constitutional Theory is a significant departure from Schmitt’s more polemical Weimar-era works not just in terms of its moderate tone. Through a comparative history of constitutional government in Europe and the United States, Schmitt develops an understanding of liberal constitutionalism that makes room for a strong, independent state. This edition includes an introduction by Jeffrey Seitzer and Christopher Thornhill outlining the cultural, intellectual, and political contexts in which Schmitt wrote Constitutional Theory; they point out what is distinctive about the work, examine its reception in the postwar era, and consider its larger theoretical ramifications. This volume also contains extensive editorial notes and a translation of the Weimar Constitution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aConstitutional lawzGermany. 0aConstitutional law. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh1 aKennedy, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeitzer, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeitzer, Jeffrey.1 aThornhill, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThornhill, Christopher.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822390589zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822390589423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822390